"McGowan H.A., Marx S.K., Soderholm J., Denholm J.","Evidence of solar and tropical-ocean forcing of hydroclimate cycles in southeastern Australia for the past 6500 years",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","10", L10705,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL042918,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953044162&partnerID=40&md5=3c6f3bcd42693d86ae11622251bd0535","Snowy Precipitation Enhancement Research Project, Snowy Hydro Limited, Monaro Highway, Cooma, NSW 2630, Australia; Climate Research Group, School of Geography, Planning and Environmental Management, University of Queensland, Brisbane, Qld 4072, Australia","McGowan, H.A., Climate Research Group, School of Geography, Planning and Environmental Management, University of Queensland, Brisbane, Qld 4072, Australia; Marx, S.K., Climate Research Group, School of Geography, Planning and Environmental Management, University of Queensland, Brisbane, Qld 4072, Australia; Soderholm, J., Climate Research Group, School of Geography, Planning and Environmental Management, University of Queensland, Brisbane, Qld 4072, Australia; Denholm, J., Snowy Precipitation Enhancement Research Project, Snowy Hydro Limited, Monaro Highway, Cooma, NSW 2630, Australia","Evidence of solar and tropical-ocean forcing of climate cycles has been found in numerous palaeoclimate records. Numerical modelling studies show physical mechanisms by which direct and indirect solar forcing may affect climate, while there is mounting evidence of solar forcing of tropical ocean-atmosphere teleconnections. This study has developed a 6500 year record of dust deposition, a proxy for regional hydroclimate variability for the Snowy Mountains region of Australia. Spectral analysis of the record provides evidence of statistically significant cycles in dust deposition of 35-43 years, 62-73 years, 161 years and 2200 years. These correlate with variability in solar irradiance and the Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO). We present evidence to support physical links between variability in solar irradiance and change in the hydroclimate of southeast Australia and suggest that the effects of global warming and solar maxima on atmospheric circulation over extra-tropical regions may exacerbate these impacts. Copyright © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric circulation; Australia; Climate cycle; Dust deposition; Numerical modelling; Pacific decadal oscillation; Palaeoclimate; Physical mechanism; Solar forcing; Solar irradiances; Solar maxima; Spectral analysis; Teleconnections; Tropical ocean; Tropical regions; Climatology; Dust; Global warming; Oceanography; Solar radiation; Spectrum analysis; Spectrum analyzers; Tropics; air-sea interaction; atmospheric circulation; atmospheric deposition; climate cycle; dust; global warming; marine atmosphere; numerical model; Pacific Decadal Oscillation; paleoclimate; solar radiation; tropical environment; Australia; Australian Alps; Snowy Mountains",,,,,,"Bard, E., Frank, M., Climate change and solar variability: What's new under the sun? (2006) Earth and Planetary Science Letters, 248 (1-2), pp. 480-493. , DOI 10.1016/j.epsl.2006.06.016, PII S0012821X06004328; Cook, E.R., Buckley, B.M., Palmer, J.G., Fenwick, P., Peterson, M.J., Boswijk, G., Fowler, A., Millennia-long tree-ring records from Tasmania and New Zealand: A basis for modelling climate variability and forcing, past, present and future (2006) Journal of Quaternary Science, 21 (7), pp. 689-699. , DOI 10.1002/jqs.1071; Franks, S.W., Assessing hydrological change: Deterministic GCMs or spurious solar correlations? (2002) Hydrol. Processes, 16, pp. 559-564. , doi:10.1002/hyp. 600; Haigh, J.D., Blackburn, M., Day, R., The response of tropospheric circulation to perturbations in lower-stratospheric temperature (2005) Journal of Climate, 18 (17), pp. 3672-3685. , DOI 10.1175/JCLI3472.1; Hendon, H.H., Thompson, D.W.J., Wheeler, M.C., Australian rainfall and surface temperature variations associated with the Southern Hemi